  "local_port": 50628,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I uninstall Modified apk by Lucky Patcher (I can only deactivate it)?",
  "response": "Uninstalling a modified APK installed via Lucky Patcher can be a bit more involved than removing standard apps, especially if the APK has been altered to resist typical uninstallation methods. Below are detailed steps you can follow to successfully remove the modified APK from your Android device:\n\n### **1. Attempt Standard Uninstallation**\n\nBefore proceeding with more advanced methods, try the basic uninstallation steps:\n\n- **Via Settings:**\n  1. **Open** your device's **Settings**.\n  2. **Navigate** to **Apps** or **Applications**.\n  3. **Find** the modified app in the list.\n  4. **Tap** on the app and select **Uninstall**.\n\n- **Via Google Play Store:**\n  1. **Open** the **Google Play Store** app.\n  2. **Tap** the **menu icon** (three horizontal lines) and select **My apps & games**.\n  3. **Locate** the modified app.\n  4. **Tap** **Uninstall**.\n\n*If these methods only allow you to deactivate the app and not uninstall it, proceed to the next steps.*\n\n### **2. Use Lucky Patcher to Uninstall**\n\nIf the app was installed or modified using Lucky Patcher, you might need to use Lucky Patcher itself to remove it:\n\n1. **Open** the **Lucky Patcher** app.\n2. **Grant** any necessary **permissions**, including **root access** if your device is rooted.\n3. **Scan** for installed apps.\n4. **Locate** the modified APK in the list.\n5. **Select** the app and choose the **Uninstall** option provided by Lucky Patcher.\n\n*Note: If Lucky Patcher is unable to uninstall the app, continue with the methods below.*\n\n### **3. Enable Developer Options and USB Debugging**\n\nTo use more advanced tools like ADB (Android Debug Bridge), you'll need to enable Developer Options:\n\n1. **Open** **Settings** on your device.\n2. **Scroll down** to **About phone**.\n3. **Tap** **Build number** **seven times** until you see a message that Developer Options are enabled.\n4. **Go back** to **Settings** and you will now see **Developer options**.\n5. **Enter** **Developer options** and **enable** **USB debugging**.\n\n### **4. Use ADB to Uninstall the App**\n\nADB allows you to execute commands on your device from a computer. Here's how to use it to remove the app:\n\n**a. Install ADB on Your Computer:**\n\n- **Windows:**\n  1. Download the **ADB platform-tools** from the [Android Developers website](https://developer.android.com/studio/releases/platform-tools).\n  2. Extract the contents to a folder (e.g., `C:\\adb`).\n\n- **macOS/Linux:**\n  1. Use a package manager like `brew` for macOS (`brew install android-platform-tools`).\n  2. Or download directly from the [Android Developers website](https://developer.android.com/studio/releases/platform-tools).\n\n**b. Connect Your Device:**\n\n1. **Connect** your Android device to your computer using a USB cable.\n2. **Authorize** your computer for USB debugging if prompted on your device.\n\n**c. Identify the Package Name:**\n\n1. **Open** a command prompt (Windows) or terminal (macOS/Linux).\n2. **Navigate** to the ADB directory, e.g., `cd C:\\adb`.\n3. **Run** the following command to list all installed packages:\n   ```\n   adb shell pm list packages\n   ```\n4. **Locate** the package name of the modified app. It often resembles `com.example.appname`.\n\n**d. Uninstall the App:**\n\n1. **Execute** the uninstall command:\n   ```\n   adb uninstall [package.name]\n   ```\n   Replace `[package.name]` with the actual package name, e.g.,\n   ```\n   adb uninstall com.example.modifiedapp\n   ```\n2. **Wait** for the confirmation message indicating the app has been uninstalled.\n\n*If you receive an error or the app persists, proceed to the next step.*\n\n### **5. Unroot Your Device (If Rooted)**\n\nSome modified apps and Lucky Patcher themselves require root access, which can complicate uninstallation. If your device is rooted, consider unrooting it:\n\n- **Use a Root Management App:**\n  - Apps like **SuperSU** or **Magisk Manager** offer options to unroot your device.\n  \n- **Manual Unrooting:**\n  - Flash the stock firmware for your device using tools like **Odin** (for Samsung devices) or **Fastboot** commands.\n\n*After unrooting, attempt to uninstall the app again via Settings or ADB.*\n\n### **6. Boot into Safe Mode and Uninstall**\n\nBooting into Safe Mode can prevent third-party apps from running, making it easier to uninstall problematic apps:\n\n1. **Press and hold** the **power button** on your device.\n2. **Tap and hold** the **Power off** option until a prompt appears asking to reboot into Safe Mode.\n3. **Confirm** to boot into **Safe Mode**.\n4. **Navigate** to **Settings > Apps**.\n5. **Find** the modified app and attempt to **uninstall** it.\n6. **Restart** your device to exit Safe Mode.\n\n### **7. Use a Third-Party Uninstaller App**\n\nThere are apps available on the Google Play Store designed to help uninstall stubborn apps:\n\n- **App Inspector**\n- **Uninstall Manager**\n- **Easy Uninstaller**\n\n*Install one of these apps and follow the in-app instructions to remove the modified APK.*\n\n### **8. Factory Reset (Last Resort)**\n\nIf all else fails and the modified app cannot be removed, performing a factory reset will erase all data and apps from your device:\n\n**Warning:** This will **delete all your data**. **Backup** important information before proceeding.\n\n1. **Open** **Settings**.\n2. **Navigate** to **System** > **Reset options**.\n3. **Select** **Erase all data (factory reset)**.\n4. **Confirm** and follow the on-screen instructions.\n\n*After the reset, the modified APK should be removed. You can then restore your data from the backup.*\n\n### **Important Considerations**\n\n- **Security Risks:** Modified APKs can pose security threats, including malware or compromised data. Always ensure apps are from trusted sources.\n  \n- **Warranty and Support:** Rooting your device or using tools like Lucky Patcher may void your warranty and make it ineligible for official support.\n\n- **Legal Implications:** Using Lucky Patcher to modify apps may violate terms of service and local laws.\n\n### **Preventive Measures**\n\n- **Avoid Using Modified Apps:** Stick to official app stores and trusted sources to minimize risks.\n  \n- **Regularly Update Apps and OS:** Keep your device updated to patch security vulnerabilities.\n  \n- **Install Antivirus Software:** Use reputable mobile security apps to detect and prevent malicious software.\n\nBy following the steps outlined above, you should be able to uninstall the modified APK installed via Lucky Patcher. If you're uncomfortable performing these actions yourself, consider seeking assistance from a professional technician or contacting your device manufacturer's support team.",
